What&#x27;s really interesting thing is that all numeric coercions go through a string coercion, and that coercion doesn&#x27;t (at least in Chrome and Firefox) have to even return a string. Presumably, the toString() method is run repeatedly until either a string or a number comes out.<p>So a simple fraction type can be done like this:<p><pre><code>    function Fraction(n, d) {
        this.n = n;
        this.d = d;
    }
    Fraction.prototype.toString = function() {
        return this.n / this.d;
    };

    //Demo
    var x = new Fraction(1, 2);
    alert(x * 38); //19
    alert(x + x); //1</code></pre>
